ce:section.ce:para:
The employment of microwave radiation for nanomaterials preparation speeds up the procedure, reducing the reaction time from many hours to just a few minutes while providing a facile and straightforward procedure with a distinctive green character. This in turn enhances the throughput for large-scale production and reduces pollution. Herein, low-cost/low-energy domestic microwave oven also eliminates the need for organic solvents or hazardous chemicals for CQDs preparation. In contrast, the reported hydrothermal [46,50–52] and dry heating [53] procedures need heating at a high temperature for a long time (
                           Table S1
                        ).

Next, various N,S-CQDs volumes were tested. For ENT, F◦/F was enhanced progressively with increasing the sensor volume to produce maximal F◦/F in the range of 1100–1300 µL; hence 1200 µL was selected as the optimum volume (
                           Fig. S6c
                        ). While for TIZ, the sensitivity was enhanced gradually by raising the sensor volume up to 600 µL. After that, there was a constant response (
                           Fig. S6c
                        ). So, the ideal volume of 900 µL was selected for TIZ assay.

Lastly, the incubation time was studied by measuring F◦/F values over a wide time interval from 0 to 60 min (
                           Fig. S6d
                        ). In the presence of the analytes, the fluorescence quenching occurred instantly, and the ratios of F◦/F remained constant for more than 60 min. These observations reflect the significant benefits of this approach with respect to rapidness, practicality, and stability.

Experimental parameters were deliberately slightly varied to check the robustness of the method, including pH (12.0 ± 0.2) for ENT, BRB volume (1000 µL ± 200), and N,S-CQDs solution volume (1200 µL ± 100 for ENT and 900 µL ± 100 for TIZ). These tiny modifications had no significant impact on the FI quenching of the N,S-CQDs, supporting the method’s robustness (
                           Table S4
                        ).

The distinctive features of the designed method, comprising simple and eco-friendly operation, short analytical time, and high sensitivity, enhanced its applicability for monitoring the content uniformity of tablets. Content uniformity is an important test in medicines to evaluate the quality of batches. The low concentration of TIZ in Caredalud® tablets (6 mg/tablet) necessitates a highly accurate and precise method for that purpose. Content uniformity testing was adopted, adhering to USP methods [14]. The calculated acceptance value (AV) was 3.46 (
                              Table S5
                           ), which is lower than the maximum allowed acceptance value (15). These findings demonstrated the TIZ uniformity in Caredalud® tablets.

Based on the previous experiments, the three most influential independent factors on F○/F were the type and amount of sugar and the acetonitrile volume. Minitab® program with 23 full factorial design introduced eight specified experiments (
                              Table S6
                           ). Minitab response optimizer determines the optimal experimental settings plus desirability values from the input factors to show the degree to which these settings meet the response (F○/F) goals. The composite desirability (D) value is from zero to one, where zero indicates undesirable conditions, while one represents the ideal case [39]. The established extraction method shows excellent desirability values of one (Table 5
                           ). As presented in the optimization plot (
                              Fig. S8
                           ), the maximum F○/F was observed when using 1000 mg of sucrose along with 500 µL of acetonitrile.

At the same time, one of the superior merits of full factorial design is providing information about the multidimensional interaction between the independent factors, which cannot be obtained by univariate optimization. As displayed in the Pareto chart of the effects (
                              Fig. S9a
                           ) and interaction plot (
                              Fig. S9b
                           ), the most significant parameter affecting F○/F is sugar type and its amount (mg) interaction (AC), but it is not statistically significant for a 95 % confidence limit. The sugar amount (mg) has a direct relationship with F○/F in the case of sucrose. On the other hand, acetonitrile volume (µL) has a negative impact on F○/F with sucrose. Also, from the main effect plot (
                              Fig. S9c
                           ) and normal plot (
                              Fig. S9d
                           ), sucrose gives a higher F○/F compared to fructose.

The ComplexGAPI pictogram (
                           Fig. S10a

                        ) of the developed method showed predominant 17 green color zones, while yellow zones were seven and only one red zone. The superiority of the green character is due to the simple sample preparation steps, simple nanomaterial synthesis within 9 min only, wasted zucchini biomass/soy sauce household user-friendly feedstocks, using water as a green solvent, minimal waste, energy-efficient spectrofluorimetric instrument, and high throughput. The yellow zones are due to the storage under normal conditions, the sampling procedure, and a waste of 10 mL for every sample. The one red zone is due to off-line sampling. It was evident that the designed method had little harmful impact on the environment. Besides, the AGREE tool reveals the exceptional greenness of the designed approach, as signified by its score of 0.82 (
                           Fig. S10b

                        ). Zones 1 and 3 are the only ones that are not green. Zone 1 is yellow, as the sample analysis was off-line, while zone 3 is associated with the analytical device positioning.
